a, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pontius","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: from the Latin personal name <i>Potentinus</i>, altered by association with the name of Pontius Pilatus (see   Pilat  ). <i>Potentinus</i> was the name of a 4th-century Christian saint who lived in the valley of the Mosel, and it was in that area and around Schleiden, south of Aachen, that his cult developed and the name became popular."],"variants":[{"name":"Pontious","meanings":["Altered form of German   Pontius  ."]},{"name":"Punches","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Pontius  ."]},{"name":"Pilat","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Jozef, Danuta, Iwan, Janina, Jerzy, Leszek, Slawomir.","Polish (<b>Piłat</b>); Czech and Slovak (<b>Pilát</b>); Croatian, Slovenian, and French: from Latin <i>(Pontius) Pilatus</i>, the name of the Roman governor of Judea who interrogated Christ, then ‘washed his hands’ of responsibility for his crucifixion. This was used as a nickname for someone who would take no responsibility, also perhaps for someone who had played the role of Pontius Pilate in a pageant or passion play. Compare   Pelot  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":16,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705183,"age":36,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705184,"age":46,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705185,"age":56,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Lady F De Pontius was born in 1050, in England. She married Ormus de Davenport in 1065, in Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1115, in her hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"1050–1115":"1050–1115","1046–1112":"1046–1112","1065–1130":"1065–1130","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1112":"1112","1046":"1046","1066":"1066","1065":"1065","1086":"1086","1130":"1130","1096":"1096","1050":"1050","Davenport, Cheshire, England":"Davenport, Cheshire, England","Davenport, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Davenport, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1050–1115":"1050–1115","1046–1112":"1046–1112","1065–1130":"1065–1130","1106":"1106","1115":"1115","1112":"1112","1046":"1046","1066